"1369","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","ABT 1343":"circa 1343","1343":"1343","1310":"1310","about 1345":"circa 1345","1408":"1408","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","UPTON, BUCKINGHAMSHIRE, ENGLAND":"Upton, Berkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","St Giles, Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Upton cum Chalvey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Upton, Buckinghamshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England"},"en":{"–1369":"–1369","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Deceased","1343–Male":"1343–Deceased","1345–1408":"1345–1408","1368–Male":"1368–Deceased","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","ABT 1343":"about 1343","1343":"1343","1310":"1310","about 1345":"about 1345","1408":"1408","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","UPTON, BUCKINGHAMSHIRE, ENGLAND":"Upton, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","St Giles, Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Upton cum Chalvey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Upton, Buckinghamshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Bulstrode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Bulstrode (Bucks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bostridge","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulstrode  ."]},{"name":"Bolstridge","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of <b>Bulstrode</b>, a habitational name from Bulstrode in Buckinghamshire, meaning ‘bull marsh’ from Old English <i>bula</i> ‘bull’ + <i>strōd</i> ‘marshy land’."]},{"name":"Boustred","meanings":["English:  see  Bulstrode  ."]},{"name":"Boulstridge","meanings":["English:  see  Bulstrode  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":8,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":39,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":64,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":77,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Montfort Bulstrode was born in Middlesex, England as the daughter of Hugh de Montford. She married John Boulstrode II in 1335, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1369, in Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England, and was buried in Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"–1369":"–1369","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1343–Male":"1343–Surnud","1345–1408":"1345–1408","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1259":"1259","1335":"1335","1368":"1368","1345":"1345","1388":"1388","ABT 1343":"umbes 1343","1343":"1343","1310":"1310","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1408":"1408","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","UPTON, BUCKINGHAMSHIRE, ENGLAND":"Upton, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","St Giles, Middlesex, England":"Middlesex, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upton cum Chalvey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Upton, Buckinghamshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chalfont St Peter, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"–1369":"–1369","1310–1388":"1310–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1343–Male":"1343–Kuollut","1345–1408":"1345–1408","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1259":"1259",